gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF016638%2F1"><gtr:id>827290A1-6243-4B18-BD8C-797874EF0C32</gtr:id><gtr:title>Novel approaches to the study of self-awareness among persons with autism, with special reference to inner speech.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F016638/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Psychologists have coined the term ?theory of mind? to describe the way in which we understand the contents of other people?s minds ? their mental states, such as their beliefs and desires. Individuals with autism have difficulties in understanding people in this way: typically, they do not understand deception, keep secrets, or communicate important information. The results of the current award holder?s research indicated, strikingly, that individuals with autism were as ?blind? to their own thoughts and feelings as they were to the thoughts and feelings of others. For example, children with autism did not seem to recognise when their movements were ?reflex? responses rather than deliberate actions, nor that any mistakes that they made were unintentional. Such results challenge current views on the nature of their difficulties.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>In a further aspect of the research, children with autism were found to be similar to people without autism in using inner language to help them complete cognitive tests. This finding contradicts reports that people with autism have a thinking style that is dominated by visual imagery. These findings are informing the design of further studies to explore why it is that people with autism have difficulty in thinking flexibly and effectively.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-10-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>95829</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>3FE48FD5-6F0C-44AA-9EC6-3174B3FADF9B</gtr:id><gtr:title>What did I say? Versus what did I think? Attributing false beliefs to self amongst children with and without autism.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of autism and developmental disorders</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/0fe2284a905df1936f472c417f5fd697"><gtr:id>0fe2284a905df1936f472c417f5fd697</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Williams DM</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2009-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0162-3257</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>pm_53cbf94bf94562bfe</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>3E9BE6AC-5265-4ED8-A185-E8C9A35299FC</gtr:id><